SnifferBike - Exploratory Data Analysis¶

by: Nicolás Salazar Beltrán (nicolas-salbe.github.io)

The SnifferBike is a data collection project with the objective of getting insights on air quality and cycling routes use in the province of Utrecht. Data is collected through an IoT sensing system mounted on the bicycles of participating citizens.

Data Description¶

The datawoordenboek_snuffelfiets dataset gathers the data collected from 190 sensors deployed during 1 week in February 2020 in the province of Utrecht.

Data Dictionary¶

  • _id: The identifier of the sample measurement.
  • sensor: The identifier of the sensor taking the measurement.
  • geom: ?
  • line: ?
  • recording_timestamp: Timestamp of the measurement.
  • date_recording: Date of the measurement.
  • delta_recording_time: Time since previous measurement (s).
  • trip_sequence: ?
  • receive_time: Timestamp of when the measurement data was received.
  • horizontal_accuracy: GPS horizontal accuracy (mm?).
  • humidity: Relative humidity (%).
  • pm10: Particulate matter smaller than 10 micrometers (ug/m^3).
  • pm1_0: Particulate matter smaller than 1.0 micrometers (ug/m^3).
  • pm2_5: Particulate matter smaller than 2.5 micrometers (ug/m^3).
  • pressure: Barometric pressure (Pa).
  • temperature: Temperature (degC).
  • vertical_accuracy: GPS vertical accuracy (mm?).
  • voc: Volatile Organic Compounds (ppb?).
  • voltage: Battery voltage (V).
  • error_code: Error code.
  • version_major: FW version major.
  • version_minor: Fw version minor.
  • acc_max: Max acceleration (m/s^2?).
  • no2: Nitrogen dioxide (ppb?).
  • distance_to_previous: Distance traveled since previous measurement (m)?
  • cumulative_distance: Cumulative distance traveled since power on?
  • speed_km_h: Speed (km/h)

Let's drop these columns.

In [9]:
df.drop(['_id','geom','line'], axis=1, inplace=True)

Regarding trip_sequence it is not clear what it means. Do different trips of the same sensor are indicated by this sequence? Can different sensors have the same trip sequence? From the data it is observed that theres's a progression in the trip sequence for each sensor. However, the trip sequence identifier is not unique among sensors.

Data is coming from 190 different sensor units. Let's store the IDs of these sensors in an array.

In [12]:
sensor_array = df.sensor.unique()

The date_recording column seems to indicate that data was taken during 1 week (7 days). Let's double check this.

In [13]:
df['date_recording'].unique()
Out[13]:
array(['2020-02-11', '2020-02-12', '2020-02-13', '2020-02-14',
       '2020-02-15', '2020-02-10', '2020-02-16'], dtype=object)

So the data was recorded from February 10, 2020 to February 16, 2020, just before the pandemic!

The SnifferBike sensor sends the measurement data to a cloud server with a certain regularity. For this analysis, the timestamp of when the data is received by the server is not relevant so we can drop receive_time. However, in a different analysis it might be worth to understand how this client-server communication can be opmitized to save energy from the battery.

Variable error_code is most likely an enumeration coding different errors that detected by the sensor firmware. Let's see which of these codes are present.

In [16]:
df['error_code'].unique()
Out[16]:
array([   0, 2048,  516,   32, 2080,  128, 2176, 2688, 2592], dtype=int64)
  • The error code seems to be a bitwise coded error. They could indicate a wrong measurement or an LTE Tx/Rx issue.

All the sensors are running FW version major 1.0. However, there are some running FW version minor 0.3, 0.5, or 0.6.

Some observations:

  • A sensor takes a new measurement every 15.3s on average
  • The mean humidity and temperature are 62% and 12.7degC, respectively, which seems off from usual winter weather.
  • The average pm10 level during that week across the province was 193 ug/m^3. This is very very high and it's probably due to an outlier in the records. Same thing seems to apply for other air quality variables.

During this week, most of the measurements happened on a Tuesday (11-02) while during the weekend the meaurements decreased signficantly. This is expected as people ride their bicycles more often during the week to go to work or school. Also, there might be people not using their bicycles at all during some days in the week. Let's get some insight on the bicycle use distribution per this week.

So assuming there's one rider per SnifferBike sensor, most of the people used their bicycle 4 times per week. Surprisingly, also many people only used their bicycle once or twice. This makes the distribution not normal and the average SnifferBike use is 3.4 times per week. There's a good opportunity for improvement here.

Numerical variables¶

Let's check if the measurements are mostly taken while moving or during standstill.

In [41]:
dist = df.groupby(by=['sensor','date_recording']).agg({'recording_timestamp':'unique','cumulative_distance':'unique'})
In [43]:
import matplotlib.dates as md
def plot_cumulative_distance_vs_time(sensor):
    sensor_df = dist.loc[sensor]
    date_index = sensor_df.index
    plt.figure(figsize = (12, 30))
    for index, date in enumerate(date_index):
        x = sensor_df.loc[date].recording_timestamp
        y = sensor_df.loc[date].cumulative_distance
        plt.subplot(len(date_index), 1, index+1)
        plt.plot(x, y, 'bo--', label=date)
        plt.title(f'Date: {date}')
        plt.xlabel('Time')
        plt.xticks(rotation=45)
        plt.gcf().axes[index].xaxis.set_major_locator(md.MinuteLocator(interval=15))
        plt.gcf().axes[index].xaxis.set_major_formatter(md.DateFormatter("%H:%M:%S"))
        plt.ylabel('Cumulative distance (m)')

    plt.suptitle(f'Cumulative distance per day \n Sensor: {sensor}', size=16)
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.subplots_adjust(top=0.92)
    plt.show()

The next figure shows the cumulative distance ridden by the user who's carrying sensor_id=2ff12c7d72b4860441ddb28da271abcf per day.

  • The amount and time of the day of the trips may vary throughout the week
In [46]:
def calculate_n_trips(x):
    n_trips = 1
    for i in range(len(x)-1):
        if x[i + 1] < x[i]:
            n_trips = n_trips + 1
    return n_trips
In [47]:
dist['n_trips'] = dist['cumulative_distance'].apply(calculate_n_trips)

In [228]:
def boxplot_metrics(x):
    Q1 = x.quantile(0.25)
    Q3 = x.quantile(0.75)
    IQR = Q3 - Q1
    Lower_Fence = Q1 - (1.5 * IQR)
    Upper_Fence = Q3 + (1.5 * IQR)
    median = x.median()
    return [median, Q1, Q3, Upper_Fence]
In [229]:
aq_table = pd.DataFrame(data=[boxplot_metrics(air_quality_df.pm10),
                              boxplot_metrics(air_quality_df.pm1_0),
                              boxplot_metrics(air_quality_df.pm2_5)],
                            columns= ['median', 'q1', 'q3', 'upper_fence'],
                                index = ['PM10', 'PM1.0', 'PM2.5'])
In [230]:
def calculate_corrected_mean(x, u_f):
    return x[x <= u_f].mean()
In [231]:
aq_table['corrected_mean'] = [calculate_corrected_mean(air_quality_df.pm10, aq_table.upper_fence[0]),
                              calculate_corrected_mean(air_quality_df.pm1_0, aq_table.upper_fence[1]),
                              calculate_corrected_mean(air_quality_df.pm2_5, aq_table.upper_fence[2])]

Conclusions¶

This EDA initally focuses on univariate analysis with the following main insights:

  • SnifferBike users are mostly regular daily commuters who make little use of their bicycle during the weekend
  • SnifferBike data is collected only during movement
  • Air quality data presented large outliers which values indicate faulty sensors, corrupted data or acquistion issues. These issues don't seem to be represented by the error codes.
  • When removing the outliers, air quality data seem to be realistic for a province like Utrecht

Reccomendations¶

Based only on the above EDA and with the available information the following can be recommended:

  • Data quantity and quality can be increased by involving bicycle users other than regular commuters
  • Collecting data also while standing still may provide valuable info on air quality behavior in a single spot during the day
  • Review logic for detecting data acquistion errors

Open questions¶

The SnifferBike data is rich of features and hides many insights yet to explore. Some extra analysis with location data available may help answering the following questions:

  • What's the expected PM in a given day, location, and weather?
  • How does battery capacity may be optimized?
  • Which are the most frequently used and better quality cycling routes?
